CSRF Token setup

Totally—once you start using real forms, wire CSRF “for real” and keep your JSON APIs/devtools out of the blast radius. Here’s a clean, battle-tested setup that fits your current factory + blueprint shape.

# 1) Initialize CSRF in your app factory

* Use **Flask-WTF**’s `CSRFProtect`.
* Keep your Jinja `csrf_token()` global (nice for templates).
* Exempt JSON/API blueprints so your contracts/devtools don’t break.

```python
# app/__init__.py (inside create_app)
from flask_wtf import CSRFProtect
try:
    from flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFError, generate_csrf
except Exception:
    CSRFError = None
    generate_csrf = lambda: ""

# --- Config knobs (works with your existing config style) ---
flask_app.config.setdefault("SECRET_KEY", "dev-override-me")
flask_app.config.setdefault("WTF_CSRF_ENABLED", True)
flask_app.config.setdefault("WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT", 3600)  # 1h
flask_app.config.setdefault("WTF_CSRF_CHECK_DEFAULT", True)  # protect form POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE
# If you serve from a subdomain, also set WTF_CSRF_SSL_STRICT, SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE, etc.

# --- CSRF setup ---
csrf = CSRFProtect()
if CSRFError is not None:
    csrf.init_app(flask_app)

# Make {{ csrf_token() }} available in templates
flask_app.jinja_env.globals["csrf_token"] = generate_csrf

# JSON error for CSRF failures (you already have this pattern)
if CSRFError is not None:
    @flask_app.errorhandler(CSRFError)
    def handle_csrf_error(e):
        return (
            {
                "error": "csrf_failed",
                "description": getattr(e, "description", "CSRF validation failed."),
            },
            400,
        )
```

# 2) Exempt the blueprints that are API-only

Protect browser forms; leave contract/devtools routes free (or add a header-based token later).

```python
# after you register blueprints; examples:
from app.slices.devtools.routes import bp as devtools_bp
from app.slices.devtools.routes import bp_api_v2 as devtools_api_v2
from app.slices.devtools.routes import bp_api_public as devtools_api_public
from app.slices.extensions.routes_admin import bp as admin_bp  # hypothetical admin UI with forms

flask_app.register_blueprint(devtools_bp)
flask_app.register_blueprint(devtools_api_v2, url_prefix="/api/v2")
flask_app.register_blueprint(devtools_api_public, url_prefix="/api")

# Exempt pure-JSON APIs (adjust as needed)
csrf.exempt(devtools_api_v2)
csrf.exempt(devtools_api_public)

# Do NOT exempt the Admin (browser) UI blueprint—those routes will use forms
# flask_app.register_blueprint(admin_bp)  # CSRF stays ON here
```

# 3) In templates: include the CSRF field

For **WTForms** forms, always include `form.hidden_tag()`; for non-WTForms forms, include the `csrf_token()` hidden input.

```html
<!-- WTForms -->
<form method="POST" action="{{ url_for('admin.entity_create_person') }}">
  {{ form.hidden_tag() }}
  <!-- fields... -->
  <button type="submit">Save</button>
</form>

<!-- Non-WTForms -->
<form method="POST" action="{{ url_for('admin.entity_create_person_raw') }}">
  <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="{{ csrf_token() }}">
  <!-- fields... -->
  <button type="submit">Save</button>
</form>
```

Tip: wrap that in a macro so you never forget:

```jinja
{# templates/macros.html #}
{% macro csrf_field() -%}
  <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="{{ csrf_token() }}">
{%- endmacro %}
```
and deploy on POST routes with
```jinja
{{ csrf_field() }}
```

# 4) AJAX / fetch POSTs from browser pages

If you later POST JSON from an HTML page (not from your pure API clients), use the **double-submit** pattern: read a token from a cookie or meta tag and send it in a header.

Template:

```html
<meta name="csrf-token" content="{{ csrf_token() }}">
```

JS:

```js
const token = document.querySelector('meta[name="csrf-token"]').getAttribute('content');

fetch("/admin/policy/update", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "X-CSRFToken": token,            // Flask-WTF accepts X-CSRFToken or X-CSRF-Token
  },
  body: JSON.stringify(payload),
});
```

Server: CSRFProtect will validate the header token automatically for same-site requests. (Keep your admin UI under CSRF; keep your `/api/*` exempt or switch them to header-tokens when you move away from devtools.)

# 5) Tests

* For request/route unit tests, either:

  * disable CSRF: `app.config["WTF_CSRF_ENABLED"] = False`, **or**
  * include a valid token in the form/headers (heavier).
* Keep your foundation tests focused on behavior; turn CSRF back on when you add UI integration tests.

# 6) Common gotchas (quick checklist)

* Make sure `SECRET_KEY` is set in non-dev envs (or CSRF will silently misbehave).
* For cross-origin admin setups, align cookie `SameSite`/`Secure` and CORS; otherwise CSRF will bite.
* If you see random 400s on long forms, extend `WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT` or re-issue a token on form render.

